candidates.title: Serialization of some X.509 types.
candidates.body: This add serialization to `rpki::x509`’s `Serial`, `Time`, and `Validity` types. It also adds it to `KeyIdentifier` but moves it to `rpki::crypto::keys` as well.

candidates.title: Revised handling of Certificates, CRLs, and all Signed Objects.
Serialize, Deserialize, and format AsResources, Ipv4Resources and Ipv6Resources
candidates.body:
Note: this is particularly useful for the Krill project where we need to persist
resources associated with Certificate Authorities.

I introduced the explicit implementations for Ipv4Resources and Ipv6Resources, in addition to IpResources and the (shortlived) IpBlocksForFamily for convenience: it allows for a straightforward Display and FromStr that can be used when (De)Serializing.

candidates.title: Implement serde traits for URI types.
Drop Fail and derive Display via derive_more.
Add TAL information to origin information.
candidates.body: This PR adds a new type `TalInfo` which currently only contains the name of the TAL but may have more information added later. A pointer to it (via an arc) is kept during validation in `ResourceCert` and is ultimately added to `RouteOriginAttestation`s. The latter keep it via a new `RoaStatus` field that is the first step towards the ability to keep invalid ROAs for statistical purposes.

candidates.title: Generate id cert
candidates.body: Would like to merge this and then continue work on making a signed CMS message for the protocol messages. I.e. create an IdCert EE, CMS, sign, verify, etc. So some refactoring is bound in that context.

candidates.title: Publication protocol -XML
candidates.body: Parsing and generating all RFC8181 XML messages

candidates.title: Start of out of band work
candidates.body:
Parses a <publisher_request> XML message and validates the included TA certificate.

So, added basic support for handling XML and Identity Certificates that will be useful for the next things that are needed for supporting the publication (and later provisioning) protocol. This stuff is in rpki-rs because both the publication server and the CA implementations will have to use this.
